Motivation

As students staying on campus, we often find ourselves in a situation where we need food but are unable to do so owing to lessons. We would then have to ask our friends to help us buy food most of the time, a task commonly delegated to those already at or on their way to a food and beverage establishment of some kind.

As of today, there are no notable apps that target food delivery within smaller communities like school hostels and even offices. Although there are plenty of food delivery services, the delivery fee for services like Foodpanda ang GrabFood are quite expensive, often taking up a quarter of the whole delivery fee. At the same time, because delivery drivers have to travel to the food place to get the order, it also results in time wasted. An additional constraint to conventional delivery apps is that it might not display every single food establishment within the vicinity, something which locals within a community would know more about.

We believe that we can tackle the existing problems by providing a free web application for members of a community to interact with each other through food requests and offers. It may also help to bring communities closer together.

Aim

Our aim for this project is to connect members of a community together through food delivery services. It is our wish that people within a community will become more bonded and willing to help each other out, and maybe expand beyond just food deliveries in the future.

We aim to create a web application that mimics the likes of GrabShare, where people requiring food can submit orders, and people already at establishments can choose to fulfill those orders. The platform will also allow people going to restaurants to post offers in advance so that others can plan ahead for lunch as well.

Comparing against existing platforms

We are all aware of the food delivery giants such as Grab, Foodpanda and Deliveroo, all of which work similarly. Lets look at the different aspects of these platforms:

  1. Location and available restaurants:

  • On startup, these platforms will require you to key in your location and then the platform will search for restaurants near you. The key limitation of these platforms is that they are only able to search for registered restaurants that provide delivery services to these platforms. Most of the time, this excludes hawker centres and coffeeshops nearby, limiting the number of choices a customer has.

  • With Lunch Hitch, we hope to provide a more extensive spread of food choices unique to each community, which will make way for more budget options to choose from. There might also be hidden jems within each community that is not recognised by the bigger platforms.

  1. Delivery fees:

  • Delivery fees on these platforms usually start at $3 onwards and free delivery is usually only available to large orders. This is because the platforms hire delivery drivers to do the delivery. What if the user is only looking to order a single dish? The delivery fees would end up consuming more than a quarter of the whole receipt which is not worth the convenience.

  • Lunch Hitch aims to minimise the delivery fees by utilising the convenience available within communities as the person going to buy food would end up going back to the community where the buyer is, where they would exchange the food and money. This eliminates the need for specialised food delivery drivers which reduces the delivery fees needed. The people offering their services may choose to state a reasonable fee depending on their convenience and the buyers can choose between the offers.

  1. Delivery time:

  • As the larger platform relies on delivery drivers around the island, delivery time can usually go up to an hour as the platform has to find a willing driver, and the driver has to travel from wherever they are to the food establishment.

  • Lunch Hitch hopes to minimise such time wastage by allowing users to post offers in advance so that buyers can plan their schedule accordingly. Users can also post when they are ready to go back from the food establishment and buyers can just take up the offer right away and expect their food to be delivered in a shorter amount of time.

Tech Stack

  1. NextJs (React Framework)

  2. Node Js

  3. MongoDB

User Stories

  1. As a community member who needs someone to buy back food, I want to be able to ask someone convenient to order food for myself.

  2. As a community member deciding where to eat from, I want to be able to see who is available at which food establishment.

  3. As a community member that is able to buy food, I want to be able to announce it to my fellow community members so that I can help them buy their food.

Future extensions

  1. As a new community member, I want to be able to know more about my food options in this community.

  2. As a community member who knows hidden gems in my community, I want to be able to share these food places with the other people in my community.

Project Scope

The scope of our project can be categorised into 3 categories: Setup, Core and Extensions.

Setup: User Login

Core: Main functions of the application

Extensions: Extra helpful functions

MileStone 1: Setup

  1. Frontend Web Routing

Set up routing for our web application from the login page to the locations page.

  1. Backend API Endpoints and Database

Set up backend API endpoints and a database for user login.

  1. Authentication using NextAuth.js

All users brought to the Lunch Hitch site are expected to login before they can gain access to the site.
